yt.com/images/2026/06/14/magazine/14Mag-Roundtable-3x2-01-Still2/14Mag-Roundtable-3x2-01-Still2-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Illustration by Mario Hugo</media:credit></media:content></item><item><title>Dutch Authorities Block $115 Million Deal by a U.S. Tech Company</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/09/technology/solvinity-kyndryl-blocked-deal-us-europe-rift.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/09/technology/solvinity-kyndryl-blocked-deal-us-europe-rift.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/09/technology/solvinity-kyndryl-blocked-deal-us-europe-rift.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The Netherlands blocked a U.S. company from buying a Dutch firm that handles its national ID system, saying it would create a “threat to the public interest.”</description><dc:creator>Adam Satariano and Ana Swanson</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 09 Jun 2026 14:52:00 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mergers and Acquisitions</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">US Foreign Policy</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Politics</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Regulation and Deregulation</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Military</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Privacy</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Cloud computing</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Donald Trump</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Kyndryl</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Solvinity</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">EU</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Netherlands</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Holland</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_geo">Europe</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/06/multimedia/00biz-dutch-trump-1-tmpk/00biz-dutch-trump-1-tmpk-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Laurens Van Putten/Agence France-Presse — Getty Images</media:credit><media:description>Willemijn Aerdts, the Dutch minister for the digital economy and sovereignty, spoke to the news media last month after blocking the acquisition of Solvinity, a Dutch tech company, by the U.S. firm Kyndryl.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Apple Reveals New A.I.-Powered Version of Its Siri Digital Assistant</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/08/technology/apple-ai-siri.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/08/technology/apple-ai-siri.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/08/technology/apple-ai-siri.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The iPhone maker revealed its new artificial intelligence products at its developer conference, the last with Tim Cook as chief executive.</description><dc:creator>Kalley Huang</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 08 Jun 2026 20:12:43 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Apple</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">iPhone</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Timothy D Cook</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Cloud computing</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Google</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/08/multimedia/apple-search-qwgh/apple-search-qwgh-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Jason Henry for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Apple held its annual conference for software developers on Monday in Cupertino, Calif.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Meta A.I. Bug Allowed Hackers to Take Over Instagram Accounts</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/09/technology/instagram-hack-ai-bug.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/09/technology/instagram-hack-ai-bug.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/06/09/technology/instagram-hack-ai-bug.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>The flaw, which Meta said it had fixed, allowed anyone to take over Instagram accounts using a bug in the company’s new artificial intelligence software.</description><dc:creator>Mike Isaac and Eli Tan</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 09 Jun 2026 20:07:42 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computer security</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mobile Apps</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Hacker (computer security)</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Facebook</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Instagram</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">WhatsApp</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark E Zuckerberg</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Barack Obama</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/06/09/multimedia/09biz-ai-instagram-1-mqhv/09biz-ai-instagram-1-mqhv-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Jason Henry for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Of the 34,000 accounts, 20,000 were breached, giving hackers access to the account holders’ email addresses, phone numbers, birth dates and other personal data.</media:description></media:content></item></channel></rss>